{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/e3.css">
{% endblock %}

{% macro result_row(rank, label, standing, excerpt) %}
<li class="e3-result" data-standing="{{ standing | lower | replace(' ', '-') }}">
  <span class="e3-result__rank">{{ rank }}</span>
  <div>
    <strong>{{ label }}</strong>
    <span class="e3-result__standing">{{ standing }}</span>
    <p>{{ excerpt }}</p>
  </div>
</li>
{% endmacro %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="exhibit-intro" aria-label="What this exhibit shows">
  <h2 class="exhibit-intro__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <div class="exhibit-intro__block">
    <h3 class="exhibit-intro__sub">The answer</h3>
    <p><strong>Hybrid search is useful now; graph expansion has not earned activation.</strong>
      Exact words find the fund questionnaire and first-quarter letter. Semantic matching
      recovers paraphrases, but also promotes a passage from the wrong manager. Entity links
      fix that example, yet the formal recall test shows no measured improvement.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="exhibit-intro__block">
    <h3 class="exhibit-intro__sub">How to read it</h3>
    <ul class="exhibit-intro__list">
      <li>Start with the ranked results and notice which error each method makes.</li>
      <li>Read the formal recall-at-ten refusal before the small top-three illustration.</li>
      <li>Follow the evidence path to see how identity and topic are established separately.</li>
      <li>Open the <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">technical
        method and provenance</a> for the ranking equations and activation rule.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="e3-panel e3-retrieval-first" aria-labelledby="e3-retrieval-title">
  <header class="e3-panel__head">
    <div>
      <p class="e3-kicker">Decision question</p>
      <h2 id="e3-retrieval-title">What did Corvid Lane say about liquidity in 2024?</h2>
    </div>
    <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="shrink">Hybrid search remains active</span>
  </header>
  <div class="e3-retrieval-grid">
    <section class="e3-ranking" aria-labelledby="e3-lexical-title">
      <h3 id="e3-lexical-title">Exact words only</h3>
      <ol>
        {{ result_row(1, 'Fund questionnaire', 'Relevant',
          'Quarterly redemption terms and the documented liquidity policy.') }}
        {{ result_row(2, 'First-quarter letter', 'Relevant',
          'The portfolio remained comfortable with liquidity.') }}
        {{ result_row(3, 'Another manager\'s questionnaire', 'Wrong manager',
          'The wording matches, but the evidence belongs to Wexford Green.') }}
      </ol>
      <p class="e3-ranking__miss"><strong>Missed paraphrase:</strong> the meeting note about
        redemption gates and cash buffers ranks fifth.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="e3-ranking" aria-labelledby="e3-hybrid-title">
      <h3 id="e3-hybrid-title">Hybrid search</h3>
      <ol>
        {{ result_row(1, 'Fund questionnaire', 'Relevant',
          'The literal liquidity answer stays first.') }}
        {{ result_row(2, 'Another manager\'s questionnaire', 'Wrong manager',
          'Semantic similarity does not prove manager identity.') }}
        {{ result_row(3, 'First-quarter letter', 'Relevant',
          'The manager\'s stated portfolio view remains in the top three.') }}
      </ol>
      <p class="e3-ranking__miss"><strong>Missed paraphrase:</strong> the meeting note improves
        to fourth, still outside the illustrative top three.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="e3-ranking e3-ranking--candidate" aria-labelledby="e3-candidate-title">
      <h3 id="e3-candidate-title">Entity-scoped candidate</h3>
      <ol>
        {{ result_row(1, 'Fund questionnaire', 'Relevant',
          'The questionnaire is directly attributed to Corvid Lane.') }}
        {{ result_row(2, 'First-quarter letter', 'Relevant',
          'The letter is directly attributed to Corvid Lane.') }}
        {{ result_row(3, 'Meeting note', 'Relevant',
          'The author-to-firm link admits the paraphrased note.') }}
      </ol>
      <p class="e3-ranking__miss">The wrong-manager result is removed in this example.
        This is an evaluated candidate, not the active retrieval method.</p>
    </section>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="e3-panel" aria-labelledby="e3-gate-title">
  <div class="power-gate e3-power-gate">
    <span class="power-gate__title" id="e3-gate-title">Formal recall@10: no measured improvement</span>
    <p>Plain hybrid search and the entity-scoped candidate both retrieve all three relevant
      records in the five-document example. Recall is therefore
      <strong>{{ "%.2f" | format(card_data.retrieval_gate.formal_metrics.baseline.recall) }}</strong>
      versus
      <strong>{{ "%.2f" | format(card_data.retrieval_gate.formal_metrics.graph_candidate.recall) }}</strong>,
      an uplift of <strong>{{ "%+.2f" | format(card_data.retrieval_gate.uplift) }}</strong>.</p>
    <p>The activation rule requires at least <strong>+0.10 absolute recall@10</strong> and a
      paired interval whose lower bound is above zero. One query cannot supply that interval.
      The candidate therefore remains inactive.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="e3-panel e3-illustration" aria-labelledby="e3-illustration-title">
  <header class="e3-panel__head">
    <div>
      <p class="e3-kicker">Mechanism, not activation evidence</p>
      <h2 id="e3-illustration-title">Illustrative top-three mechanism check</h2>
    </div>
  </header>
  <p>In the top three only, the entity-scoped candidate recovers three of three relevant
    records instead of two of three: recall moves from
    <strong>{{ "%.2f" | format(card_data.retrieval.illustrative_k3.baseline.recall) }}</strong>
    to
    <strong>{{ "%.2f" | format(card_data.retrieval.illustrative_k3.graph_candidate.recall) }}</strong>.
    This explains the mechanism; it does not override the formal refusal above.</p>
</section>

<section class="e3-panel" aria-labelledby="e3-path-title">
  <header class="e3-panel__head">
    <div>
      <p class="e3-kicker">Connected evidence</p>
      <h2 id="e3-path-title">One evidence path, two independent checks</h2>
    </div>
  </header>
  <p>The stored relationships establish who produced the evidence and what it discusses.
    They do not store a direct manager-to-topic conclusion.</p>

  <div class="e3-evidence-path" role="img" aria-label="A first-quarter letter branches to an identity path through Elena Voss and Corvid Lane Capital, and a topic path through a liquidity view to the liquidity theme.">
    <article class="e3-path-node e3-path-node--source">
      <span>Source record</span><strong>First-quarter letter</strong>
    </article>
    <div class="e3-path-branch e3-path-branch--identity">
      <span class="e3-path-relation">authored by</span>
      <article class="e3-path-node"><span>Person</span><strong>Elena Voss</strong></article>
      <span class="e3-path-relation">employed by</span>
      <article class="e3-path-node"><span>Manager</span><strong>Corvid Lane Capital</strong></article>
    </div>
    <div class="e3-path-branch e3-path-branch--topic">
      <span class="e3-path-relation">expresses</span>
      <article class="e3-path-node"><span>View</span><strong>Liquidity view</strong></article>
      <span class="e3-path-relation">about theme</span>
      <article class="e3-path-node"><span>Theme</span><strong>Liquidity</strong></article>
    </div>
    <article class="e3-path-endpoint">
      <span>Underwriting question</span>
      <strong>What did Corvid Lane say about liquidity?</strong>
      <small>The question is a presentation endpoint, not a stored graph relation.</small>
    </article>
  </div>

  <aside class="e3-wrong-branch" aria-label="Wrong-manager branch">
    <span>Other-manager questionnaire</span>
    <span class="e3-path-relation">attributed to</span>
    <strong>Wexford Green Capital</strong>
    <small>Muted because it answers a similar question for the wrong manager.</small>
  </aside>

  <div class="e3-source-picker" aria-labelledby="e3-source-picker-title">
    <h3 id="e3-source-picker-title">Inspect the supporting sentence</h3>
    <div class="e3-source-picker__controls">
      <button type="button" aria-pressed="true" data-source-doc="L-2024Q1"
        data-source-label="First-quarter letter" data-as-of="March 2024"
        data-source-span="In the first quarter we remained comfortable with portfolio liquidity and kept the book positioned for a range of outcomes.">First-quarter letter</button>
      <button type="button" aria-pressed="false" data-source-doc="DDQ-2024"
        data-source-label="Fund questionnaire" data-as-of="February 2024"
        data-source-span="The fund offers quarterly redemption with ninety day notice and maintains a documented liquidity policy.">Fund questionnaire</button>
      <button type="button" aria-pressed="false" data-source-doc="MTG-2024-05"
        data-source-label="Meeting note" data-as-of="May 2024"
        data-source-span="The portfolio manager explained redemption gates under stress and how cash buffers are sized against withdrawals.">Meeting note</button>
    </div>
    <blockquote id="e3-provenance" class="e3-provenance" aria-live="polite">
      <strong data-provenance-name>First-quarter letter</strong>
      <span data-provenance-date>March 2024</span>
      <p data-provenance-span>In the first quarter we remained comfortable with portfolio
        liquidity and kept the book positioned for a range of outcomes.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="e3-panel" aria-labelledby="e3-brief-title">
  <header class="e3-panel__head">
    <div>
      <p class="e3-kicker">Meeting preparation</p>
      <h2 id="e3-brief-title">What the allocator can ask next</h2>
    </div>
  </header>
  <div class="e3-brief-grid">
    <article><h3>Liquidity terms</h3><p>How would the ninety-day notice period and
      quarterly dealing terms behave during a stressed redemption wave?</p></article>
    <article><h3>Cash buffers</h3><p>What determines the size of the cash buffer, and
      which sleeves would be raised first?</p></article>
    <article><h3>Missing evidence</h3><p>Return and position panels are not attached to
      this fictional manager identity, so the brief does not borrow another manager's figures.</p></article>
  </div>
</section>

<aside class="e3-honesty" role="note">
  <h2>Limit of the exhibit</h2>
  <p>All documents, people, firms, and relationships are authored synthetic examples. A live
    fact would render only after extraction precision and recall each reach at least 0.8 for
    every required field. Retrieved material prepares a human conversation; it never becomes
    a manager score or an automatic decision.</p>
</aside>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The active method combines literal and semantic retrieval, then fuses their rank positions.
  The evaluated extension uses one-hop entity scoping: documents attributed to the manager,
  plus documents authored by people employed there.</p>
<p>Every displayed fact retains a source sentence and date. The browser only switches among
  those authored source records. It does not traverse relationships or recompute retrieval.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/e3-knowledge.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
